        "page": "6",
        "text": "From Urban West Ventures, LLC 1.949.544.5208 Wed Aug 18 15:59:55 2010 MST Page 4 of 6 projections are conservative and achievable. Likely they will be easily surpassed. In the attached pro forma we estimate initial daily average of 400 cars, which is a capture rate of the street traffic of approximately 0.5% (400 cars divided by 80,000 cars). This measurement of capture rate is a standard in the car wash industry and a cormerstone in the evaluation of site acquisition. According to national surveys published in car wash trade magazines, an average capture rate is 1% of the daily traffic volume. Mike Shullman\u2019s chain, Russell Speeders, has an average capture rate of 1.34% .(the equivalent of 1,072 cars per day at Five Points) Thus, we feel that a 0.5% capture rate is conservative to start. We have also assumed that the first month will yield zero sales, and months two and three will yield half of the target first year monthly sales as a result of the rehabilitation and free car washes that will be part of the promotions. Given that the menu of options for services will be similar to options provided at other Russell Speeders locations, the ticket average, based on similar sales techniques, should be consistent as well as expenses and detail sales. Our estimated total project cost, including the acquisition, soft costs, rehabilitation, contingency and marketing totals $4,325,000. Projected year one cash flow, which includes some rental income from the currently rented industrial property, should be approximately $530,000 before debt service. With assumed debt at 75% of the total project cost and interest at 6.5% amortizing over 20 years, the initial debt service coverage is projected to be 1.83 which is exceptional. With operations stabilized and growing, year two net operating income is projected at approximately 1,000,000 (again the year two capture rate is below the industry average at .55%) which yields debt service coverage of 3.47. Using a capitalization rate of ten which slightly undervalues the property compared to typical Califomia car wash sales, in year one the loan to value is estimated to be 61% and in year two 32%. Please see the attached summary and ten year pro forma. Mike Shullman and Stewart Winkler have been carefully monitoring the car wash market from San Diego to Los Angeles for nearly two years with extremely selective and conservative c"
