        "page": "229",
        "text": "MARKET / SUBMARKET INFORMATION Old Greenwich, Connecticut A coastal neighborhood situated within Fairfield County, Old Greenwich is in the southeast corner of the town of Greenwich. It is bounded by the Long Island Sound and the neighboring city of Stamford. Established in 1640, the town has held onto its historical roots, allowing it to be deemed the oldest neighborhood in Greenwich. Consequently, Old Greenwich has a substantial amount of history throughout the town. Today, the region is primarily a suburban residential area with a solid commercial base and a good industrial sector. In general, the communities in southwestern Fairfield County and along the coast of the Long Island Sound are more prestigious, middle-to upper-Income areas. Based on Bloomberg's annual report regarding \"America's 100 Richest Places,\" Old Greenwich ranks seventh (7th) among the wealthiest communities in the country. Although Old Greenwich has a population of around 6,100 according to the 2010 census, it maintains a small-town feel for locals and visitors alike. There are plenty of offerings from shopping to dining. The downtown shopping district features a block-long strip of mom-and-pop boutiques along with popular and diverse restaurants. There are numerous attractions such as clean beaches to major public green spaces. Considered a family-oriented town, Old Greenwich has a highly rated public and private school system. The elementary school through high school boasts A-A+ ratings on niche.com, making the area a prime attraction for families. The County of Fairfield is home to four of Connecticut's most dynamic metropolitan areas (Stamford, Norwalk, Bridgeport and Danbury). Its strategic location in the Southwestern sector of Connecticut offers easy access to the New York Metropolitan area and all of New England. As a result, the region has a diverse workforce with nineteen (19) Fortune 1000 corporations stationed within Fairfield County. There are multiple public and private colleges and universities settled in the County, such as Fairfield University, Sacred Heart University, and University of Bridgeport. The primary means of transportation throughout the region is by automobile. Interstate 95, which extends along the entire eastern seaboard from Maine to Florida, is the major area highway. The Merritt Parkway, which runs parallel to 1-95, traverses the county east and west "
